<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>133</anchor>   <addr>axt-0003</addr>  <route>axt-0003.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>8</month> <day>18</day></date> <authors><author><link href="ayberkt.xml" type="local">Ayberk Tosun</link></author> </authors> <title>Intuition on the notion of a domain</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  In the words of <link href="martin-escardo.xml" type="local" title="Martín H. Escardó">Martín Escardó</link>: A <em>domain</em> is a set of
  concrete finite elements together with infinite, ideal elements such that the
  ideal elements are characterised uniquely by their finite approximations.
</p><p>  There are different ways of capturing this mathematically, to varying degrees of
  precision. These include <link href="axt-001T.xml" type="local" title="Continuous dcpo">continuous</link> and <link href="axt-001S.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic dcpo">algebraic</link> dcpos.
</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>134</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-001T</addr>  <route>axt-001T.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="dana-scott.xml" type="local">Dana S. Scott</link></author> </authors> <title>Continuous dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>135</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-001S</addr>  <route>axt-001S.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>25</day></date> <authors><author><link href="dana-scott.xml" type="local">Dana S. Scott</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebraic dcpo</title> <meta name="source"><b>Theorem 11.5</b> of <link href="dtfofp.xml" type="local" title="Domain-Theoretic Foundations of Functional Programming">Streicher</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A dcpo <tex>(D,  \sqsubseteq )</tex> is called <em>algebraic</em> if for every <tex>x  \in  D</tex>  the set <tex>\{ c  \in   \mathcal{K} (D)  \mid  c  \sqsubseteq  x \}</tex> is directed and has <tex>x</tex> as
  its join.
